<TEXT>
columbia gas is dropping its request to 
make naturalgas customers pay for costs associated with a visit by 
vice president dan quayle last year 
columbia gas had sought customer reimbursement for 703000 in 
costs related to the promotion of a bus powered by natural gas 
quayle unveiled the bus during a visit to ohio on sept 8 
the change in the companys position came friday a day after 
quayles press secretary said the vice president was sending a 
letter to columbia gas asking that the cost be dropped from a 42 
million rateincrease request pending before state utility 
regulators 
quayle said the companys attempt to recover the costs was 
outrageous 
columbia gas spokesman alan crockett said the companys decision 
to withdraw its request for the reimbursement had nothing to do 
with the vice president 
the company said in a statement certainly we want to assure 
that the many benefits of clean air technologies such as the 
natural gas bus are kept in proper focus the attention that now 
surrounds our request to recover these costs has shifted the focus 
of our original intent in developing this important new 
technology 
quayles press secretary david beckwith said the vice 
president had no idea the bus costs might be passed to gas 
customers beckwith said quayle assumed the utility would absorb 
the costs 
the use of my visit to columbus as an excuse to soak the 
ratepayers is outrageous beckwith quoted quayle as saying 
of the 703000 reimbursement ohio customers were asked to pick 
up 428839 of the bill with the remainder spread among customers 
in kentucky maryland new york and pennsylvania 
</TEXT>
