<DOCNO> AP900210-0002 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here are some facts figures and 
theories about venus the planet visited early today by the 
jupiterbound galileo spacecraft 
diameter about 7520 miles or 95 percent as wide as earth and 
sixth largest of the solar systems nine known planets 
mass venus weighs about 82 percent as much as earth 
atmosphere about 96 percent carbon dioxide and most of the rest 
nitrogen but with thick clouds of sulfuric acid and water vapor 
the atmosphere traps heat in a runaway greenhouse effect that 
scientists believe evaporated liquid water long ago 
surface conditions temperature about 900 degrees fahrenheit 
crushing atmospheric pressure 90 times that on earth 
day length venus rotates on its axis very slowly so one day on 
venus equals 243 earth days its rotation is retrograde so the sun 
rises in the west and sets in the east 
year length venus orbits the sun once every 225 earth days 
distance from the sun venus is the second planet from the sun 
orbiting at a distance of 672 million miles it is closer to earth 
than any other planet other than the sun and moon venus is the 
brightest object in earths skies 
moons none 
geology earthbased and spacecraft radar revealed hundreds of 
thousands of volcanoes on the venusian lowlands although 
scientists dont yet know if any are active venus also has 
meteorite impact craters and continentlike highlands with towering 
peaks that dwarf earths tallest mountains scientists suspect 
giant plates of rock may move in venus crust in a process vaguely 
like continental drift on earth 
gravity about 89 percent as strong as on earth 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900210-0003 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here are key events for the galileo 
spacecrafts looping sixyear trip to jupiter the solar systems 
largest planet 
oct 18 1989 galileo is released from the cargo bay of space 
shuttle atlantis then an inertial upper stage booster launches the 
spacecraft on its long voyage 
nov 911 1989 controllers order multiple firings of 
galileos thrusters for the first of about 30 course correction 
maneuvers 
dec 22 1989 thrusters fire again for second course 
correction 
feb 9 1990 galileo swoops near venus for its first gravity 
assist maneuver using the planets gravity to increase the 
spacecrafts speed to help it reach jupiter galileo makes photos 
and measurements of venus storing them on an onboard recorder 
late october 1990 galileo plays back to earth the photos and 
measurements it made near venus 
dec 8 1990 galileo passes within 600 miles of earth making 
photos and measurements during its second gravity assist 
maneuver which will help aim it toward jupiter 
oct 29 1991 the spacecraft swoops within 600 miles of 
asteroid gaspra taking pictures and measurements 
dec 8 1992 galileo zooms about 185 miles above earths 
surface in the third and final gravity assist maneuver needed 
to hurl it toward jupiter 
aug 28 1993 if galileo has adequate propellant supplies it 
passes 600 miles from asteroid ida for photos and measurements 
july 1995 the spacecraft separates into a 760pound galileo 
probe and a 4890pound galileo orbiter both continue toward 
jupiter 
dec 7 1995 the probe and orbiter arrive at jupiter the 
probe plunges into the planets atmosphere relaying measurements 
to the orbiter then is destroyed by intense atmospheric pressure 
the orbiter speeds about 600 miles from the moon io and its 
sulfurspewing volcanoes and geysers then goes into orbit around 
jupiter 
december 1995october 1997 the orbiter circles jupiter making 
photos and measurements of the giant planet and the moons europa 
ganymede and callisto 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

