<TEXT>
the democratic uprisings that have swept 
three continents stunned the world with their apparent suddenness 
but reform leaders say those impressions are misleading 
the struggle for democratic freedoms is always long and never 
easy said li lu a chinese student leader who is on his 
countrys most wanted list and was forced to flee after the 
massacre of protesters in beijing last spring 
nonviolent reform was the focus friday as about 180 political 
leaders scholars and journalists from around the world met for the 
first time to discuss the dramatic changes in recent months from 
the berlin wall to soweto 
everyone here is representative of different movements that 
are constantly in the headlines said roger powers of the 
cambridgebased albert einstein institution sponsor of the 
threeday conference 
our contention is that you cant understand international 
politics today without understanding nonviolent methods because 
those methods are behind the changes going on everywhere around the 
world he said 
leaders and scholars of democratic movements in china south 
africa the soviet union eastern europe and elsewhere spent the 
day exchanging strategies and stories of reform 
one of the principles of nonviolence is to weigh down the 
opponent until you outlast the resistance said patrick lekota a 
leader of the united democratic front of south africa each 
campaign is a springboard for advance 
in south africa he said boycotts strikes and external 
political economic and moral pressure have taken the democratic 
movement a long way toward fundamental reforms 
president fw de klerk made history last week by announcing the 
most sweeping reforms since the countrys apartheid system was put 
in place in 1948 
but lekota said those changes were set in motion long before de 
klerk announced his dramatic initiatives which include the planned 
release of jailed african national congress leader nelson mandela 
and the lifting of a ban on more than 20 outlawed antiapartheid 
groups 
de klerk did not just wake up one day with a heart of gold 
he said it was our steady pressure that took us to the point 
where he could no longer ignore us 
lu who is studying at columbia university said the story in 
china has been somewhat different but the movements impact cannot 
be overlooked and must not be misunderstood 
the goal of the students was to make the people aware of their 
situation lu said the next step is real practical 
change 
such changes could also be spurred by the recent popular 
uprisings across the soviet bloc and radical changes in the soviet 
union where this week the communists voted to end oneparty rule 
lu said 
we have a very conservative dictatorship in china he said 
but they no longer have anywhere to hide the changes are 
everywhere around them 
among the other panelists participating in fridays session were 
raymundas rayatskas one of the founders of lithuanian popular 
front and u tin maung win a leader of the committee for the 
restoration of democracy in burma 
activists said the roads had been long and pitted for 
nonviolent movements that stretch back to the chinese cultural 
revolution of the 1960s the prague spring of 1968 or the soweto 
riots of 1976 
political transformation is seldom swift but the boycotts 
rallies and marches are fired by necessity experts said 
when people are poor their stomachs empty and their minds 
oppressed they have no choice but to use nonviolence as a 
weapon said mubarak awad of the palestinian center for the study 
of nonviolence 
</TEXT>
