<DOCNO> AP900210-0010 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
mexican authorities say they are trying to 
figure out why fewer gray whales than usual are showing up in baja 
california waters to give birth this year 
it will have to be researched said graciela de la garza 
head of conservation for the department of ecology and urban 
development 
marine mammal experts said 2000 whales could be expected to 
enter the lagoons during a normal calving season but mexican 
authorities interviewed thursday and friday said only 12 to 20 
whales have been spotted 
a us group said friday that 40 to 60 whales were spotted in 
recent days at san ignacio one of four bays the whales use for 
breeding 
de la garza said it was the first time such low numbers had been 
observed so late in the season 
however anelio aguayo a marine mammal expert at the national 
university in mexico city cautioned that there are frequently 
transitory variations in the numbers of whales in the different 
lagoons 
we need to wait for the end of the season and then see what 
the outcome is he said 
the whales use the vizcaino biosphere reserve a 6millionacre 
protected zone because high salt content helps pregnant females 
float and give birth said jorge hernandez a marine biologist for 
a committee that oversees the reserve 
they calve in the bays of san ignacio guerrero negro magdalena 
and ojo de liebre or eye of the hare known to whale fans in the 
united states as scammons lagoon 
the whales usually begin arriving in the first week of november 
by april most have left for alaskan waters hernandez said 
but the few that arrived this year didnt start appearing until 
middecember said ulises cesena montano the reserves interagency 
coordinator 
we dont know the reasons there are only hypotheses he 
said 
the group of 100 an ecological group of mexican artists and 
intellectuals has suggested that an industrial salt plant in the 
reserves buffer zone may be damaging water quality or that the 
whales may have been affected by the exxon valdez oil spill in 
alaskan waters last year 
but de la garza and cesena discounted those ideas 
cesena said the prevailing theory is that an unusual cold 
current is keeping the whales away from their accustomed warmwater 
haunts in places the current is less than a mile from land he 
said 
the temperature strength and exact route of the current dubbed 
the corriente de la nina are still being studied and an aerial 
search is being conducted for whales in the pacific hernandez said 
once the cold water is past maybe the whales will appear 
cesena said he said only 20 whales have been spotted so far de la 
garza said the number could be as low as 12 
but mark palmer conservation director of ocean alliance based 
in oakland calif said in a telephone interview that a group of 
whalewatchers sponsored by oceanic society expeditions has observed 
40 to 60 gray whales in the san ignacio lagoon in recent days 
de la garza said the variations are not necessarily cause for 
alarm there can be delays in any species migration she said 
the species was hunted to the verge of extinction but recovered 
substantially after hunting was prohibited following world war i 
palmer said the gray whale population is estimated at 17000 to 
20000 from studies conducted over several years 
he said the varying figures suggest a need for a better survey 
in one part of the lagoons they probably dont have a good 
overall picture palmer said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

