a united germany could stay with the 
nato alliance and still carve out a special military status for the 
present territory of east germany alliance officials and analysts 
say 
the overriding concern for the north atlantic treaty 
organization is that a reunified germany maintain its ties to the 
west 
nato secretary general manfred woerner a west german says 
there is no acceptable alternative to germany remaining anchored 
in the atlantic alliance 
the new york times today reported that us secretary of state 
james a baker iii suggested a single germany with less than full 
membership in nato might be acceptable 
we favor a continued membership in or association with 
nato the newspaper quoted baker as saying in moscow where he 
was meeting with soviet officials he did not elaborate 
east german premier hans modrow has suggested that a combined 
nation be neutral west germany belongs to the 16nation nato and 
east germany is one of the seven countries in the sovietled warsaw 
pact 
but us and nato officials have dismissed the idea of such a 
large neutral state in europe 
a drifting neutral germany cannot be a solution given the 
countrys geostrategic position and its political economic and 
military potential woerner said in a recent speech in west 
germany 
woerner and president bush will discuss the german question and 
other nato issues this weekend at the presidential retreat at camp 
david md 
hansdietrich genscher west germanys foreign minister has 
sketched out another plan for a successor nation it would remain 
part of nato but only the territory of west germany would be tied 
to its military structure nato would not extend its forces farther 
east 
baker has registered his support for genschers plan 
a formula would have to be found for dealing with the large 
contingents of forces stationed in both germanys 
about 380000 soviet troops are stationed in east germany more 
than 200000 american soldiers are based across the border in west 
germany belgium britain france and the netherlands have an 
additional 100000 or so troops there 
negotiators for nato and the warsaw pact are bargaining in 
vienna to cut forces tanks artillery and other nonnuclear arms 
in europe bush recently suggested that washington and moscow set 
equal ceilings of 225000 troops in all of europe with 195000 
troops in central europe which would include both germanys 
on friday soviet leader mikhail s gorbachev proposed a limit 
of 195000 troops for both sides in all of europe 
some have raised the possibility that to ease the kremlins 
fears about a united germany soviet troops could remain in place 
in a guantanamo fashion that refers to the presence of us 
naval forces in guantanamo bay in communist cuba 
there are precedents for what some call a la carte 
membership in nato 
spain and france are members of nato but keep their forces 
outside the joint military structure spain also does not allow the 
storing of nuclear weapons on its soil 
norway which shares a border with the soviet union is a member 
of the integrated military structure but has set out certain 
peacetime limitations 
no foreign troops are stationed on its soil no alliance forces 
take part in military exercises in the extreme northern part of the 
country nuclear weapons also cannot be warehoused on its territory 
indeed west germany itself offers a special case 
the bonn government joined the western alliance in 1955 
becoming its 15th member 
as part of membership it had to put its military forces except 
for a defensive territorial army under the alliance command it is 
the only country to have assigned to the joint structure in 
peacetime 
