prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki has 
asked 17 creditor nations if his noncommunist government could 
halt payments on polands 40 billion foreign debt officials said 
mazowiecki requested a suspension of payments because we are 
at the moment introducing a very difficult economic reform 
program government spokesman zbigniew augustynowicz said in an 
interview 
mazowiecki made the request friday in a letter sent to fellow 
government leaders in the paris club which meets next week 
the club an informal grouping of representatives of western 
creditor nations that gathers occasionally in paris was expected 
to take up polands debt problems wednesday 
about 65 percent or 26 billion of polands hardcurrency debt 
is owed to 17 governments in the club 
poland which has had a noncommunist government since last 
summer has been paying about 15 billion annually to service its 
western debt the largest such obligation in eastern europe 
those payments while falling far short of polands obligations 
consume nearly all of the countrys net export earnings leaving 
poland little money to invest in rebuilding its dilapidated economy 
however major debt rescheduling with the paris club was refused 
until polands new solidarityled government and the international 
monetary fund could reach agreement on a tough adjustment program 
to reform polands economy the plan took effect jan 1 and was 
formally approved by the imf executive board last week 
according to augustynowicz the letter asks specifically that 
the creditor governments 
permit poland to suspend all paris club debt payments 
including interest and principal for 1989 and 1990 
consider freezing the countrys western debt at its current 
level of 40 billion this would require the paris club governments 
to exert pressure on their countries commercial banks which hold 
most of the rest of the 40 billion debt 
seek a longterm solution to the polish debt problem that 
would go in the direction of outright debt reduction 
the paris club had been expected to offer poland a 
magnanimous restructuring of the debt allowing it to stretch 
out 5 billion in payments due the next two years over 10 years a 
us finance official david c mulford said last month 
most of the debt was accumulated during the 1970s by the 
communist government under thenparty leader edward gierek 
in the 1970s communist authorities borrowed and spent western 
money freely on illconceived investment projects and on food and 
consumer goods in an attempt to win public affection later 
communist governments acknowledged that the money was wasted 
when polands economy slumped at the end of the 1970s and the 
beginning of the 1980s the country was no longer able to keep up 
payments and mounting interest doubled the debt to the 40 billion 
level by this year 
