<TEXT>
a pentagon decision to shelve contingency 
plans for fighting a war with the soviet union in iran eliminates a 
strategic doctrine that has guided us policy in the persian gulf 
for four decades 
during that time us military planners have prepared for a 
soviet attack southward through iran toward the gulfs vital oil 
fields the americans would block it in the rugged zagros mountain 
range which parallels much of irans gulf coastline 
according to published accounts in washington the pentagons 
defense planning guidance report for 199297 just approved by 
defense secretary dick cheney declares that neither a soviet 
invasion of iran nor the us ability to counter it is now 
considered credible 
according to reports the pentagon document directs military 
planners to formulate a new strategy that assumes soviet military 
strength will be reduced through negotiations on conventional force 
levels in europe and that future threats to the gulf would 
originate elsewhere 
although not named potential adversaries evidently include 
iran which is hostile to saudi arabia and still technically at war 
with iraq despite their 1988 ceasefire iraq stronger as a 
result of its military triumph in the eightyear gulf war is also 
mistrusted by some arab states 
the zagros strategy by some accounts dates back to 1946 when 
thensoviet leader josef stalin hoping to gain access to the 
gulfs warmwater ports tested his former world war ii allies by 
attempting to annex territory in northern iran 
the effort was thwarted by us and british diplomacy at the 
united nations american policy has recognized moscows interest in 
obtaining access to the gulf and perhaps dominating the 
oilproducing arab states along its shores 
from those days until now according to foreign policy expert 
gary sick us leaders have seen iran as the most likely place 
outside europe where a ussoviet clash might escalate into 
another world war 
the united states had the advantage until its close ally shah 
mohammad reza pahlavi was overthrown in 1979 his islamic 
fundamentalist successor ayatollah ruhollah khomeini rejected 
ties with both washington and moscow making iran a hostile setting 
for both superpowers in the event of a showdown 
the us doctrine of blocking soviet moves through iran acquired 
new importance after moscow invaded neighboring afghanistan in 1979 
and deployed warships near the gulf 
although undoubtedly influenced by the easing of eastwest 
tensions the shift toward a new pentagon strategy for the gulf 
reflects thinking that predates the soviet bloc upheavals by at 
least a year us sources say 
as early as 1988 these sources have said military analysts 
were giving less weight to the prospect of a us counteroffensive 
in iran in favor of direct defense of the gulf itself 
this change the sources said was based partly on a belief that 
neither the soviets nor the united states could long sustain major 
military operations in a country where both terrain and politics 
are hostile the zagros mountains have peaks of up to 18000 feet 
in december 1988 the retiring commander of us central 
command marine gen george b crist was quoted as saying he had 
proposed to the us joint chiefs of staff a new plan for deploying 
us land sea and air forces to defend key objectives from the 
northern gulf to the strait of hormuz 600 miles to the southeast 
crist said new intelligence indicated the soviets would try to 
seize such objectives rather than mount a major land thrust through 
iran 
any new strategy would require at least prolonging the 
40yearold american naval presence in the gulf soon to be cut 
from 10 to seven ships in addition a nineship carrier group is 
in the arabian sea 
but how large additional forces could be maintained without land 
bases nearby is unclear while privately welcoming the us 
military presence the politically sensitive gulf states refused 
during the iraniraq war to allow us bases on their territory 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
richard pyle has covered the persian gulf for 
the associated press since 1987 
</TEXT>
