<TEXT>
the vanishing image of the harddrinking 
chainsmoking reporter has lost more of its varnish americas 
oldest press club has closed its doors 
the 98yearold pen amp pencil club survived the death of more 
than a dozen philadelphia periodicals but now has fallen victim to 
the changing drinking habits of journalists and the highcrime 
neighborhood it moved to in 1986 
more than a hundred people close to half the clubs dwindling 
membership jammed the bar friday night threatening the beer 
supply 
stories were swapped about the card games in the 1950s that 
would bring police raids the time a couple got caught in the 
restroom in an amorous clinch the numerous raunchy parties 
the club chartered in 1892 and billed as americas oldest press 
club by local newspapers and the national press club has seen a 
host of famous names cross its doorway 
red smith and damon runyon were members guests included mae 
west william jennings bryan and former mayor frank rizzo 
us presidents hoover coolidge and taft imbibed at the clubs 
bar according to club history taft skipped out on his tab 
