page atmosphere there 
the journalist as harddrinker was firmly entrenched in 
americana after the premiere of the front page a play of the 
1920s that portrayed reporters as hoodlumesque halfdrunken 
caballeros 
inquirer reporter tom belden said the changing drinking habits 
of reporters caused the clubs demise 
when he first began coming to the club in 1979 there were a 
dozen or so single men who would drop 20 to 50 a night they kept 
the bar going themselves 
but journalism is no longer dominated by single men he said 
and married people tend to stay home with their family more often 
and drink more orange juice than liquor he added 
the national press club based in washington dc estimated 
that 22 press clubs closed between 1982 and 1985 
the philadelphia club had been located above a diner about 
halfway between buildings housing the inquirer and the evening 
bulletin when the bulletin folded in 1982 the club decided to 
move closer to the inquirer building 
that move was seen by many as the beginning of the end 
we thought people getting off work in the afternoon would 
wander over for a drink said fish who was on the clubs board 
at the time but every time i came over thered be nobody here 
