rightwing paramilitary groups funded by drug 
traffickers pose the biggest threat to human rights in colombia and 
investigations of their crimes are often hindered by police 
according to a un report 
the report published friday urged colombian authorities to 
dismiss anyone in the armed forces or police found to have 
cooperated with the death squads 
the report by amos wako to be presented to the un human 
rights comission said that for many years murder had been the main 
cause of death among adults in colombia 
it called for an international fund be established to help 
protect judges and witnesses and more international to increase the 
number of police investigators and improve their training 
in the first nine months of last year 2337 people lost their 
lives as a result of political and military conflict the report 
said 
it said 603 victims were whitecollar workers most of them 
government employees killed in retaliation for the governments 
clampdown on drug traffickers 
the report said another 456 victims were peasants who were labor 
activists or suspected of sympathizing with the various 
antigovernment guerrilla groups 
most died at the hands of the estimated 140 paramilitary groups 
trained and financed by drug barons and operating closely with 
elements in the armed forces and police it said 
it said in some cases police ignored the crimes hindered 
investigations or offered safe conduct passes to paramilitary 
members 
wako cited concerns by some private human rights groups in 
colombia that existing foreign aid was mainly military in character 
and focused more on countering antigovernment guerrillas rather 
than drug traffickers or paramilitary squads 
the report also criticized violence and blackmail tactics used 
by leftwing guerrillas it welcomed efforts by president virgilio 
barcos government to promote dialogue with the insurgency 
movements 
wako a kenyan wrote the report following a 10day un mission 
to colombia in october 
