<TEXT>
larry rigby gambled five years ago on a 
biomedical device that mimics the human lung if it pays off 
beating long odds his tiny company could become a lifegiving 
giant 
rigby a venture capitalist teamed up with dr jd mortensen 
to found cardiopulmonics inc maker of the experimental lung 
device that was implanted in a teenager who died earlier in the 
week 
the operation was the first time a person had received the 
intravascular oxygenator dubbed ivox which has been approved by 
federal regulators in patients who have little chance of survival 
the device which works like a lung is a 20inch bundle of 
hollow polypropylene fibers designed to handle as much as half the 
bodys oxygen delivery and elimination of carbon dioxide it was 
designed for patients suffering acute but reversible lung disease 
or injury 
i think its very promising technology rigby said we 
could be a 100 million company in five years if the technology is 
what we think it is 
rigby said he was pleased that the instrument functioned as 
expected during its first human trial but sounded a cautionary 
note 
this is research he said you just cant make leaping 
conclusions from one example 
under guidelines approved by the us food and drug 
administration the ivox will be tested in up to 10 people who 
require 100 percent oxygen to detect possible tissue damage 
suffering from respiratory distress syndrome melicia mimi 
harvey 16 of arthur city texas died wednesday of pulmonary 
failure at lds hospital four days after the implant tim madden a 
spokesman at the hospital said there were no clinical 
complications from the device 
if the device proves successful up to 200000 patients annually 
in the united states and more in japan and europe could be 
recipients rigby said but the company which employs 32 people 
