<TEXT>
secessionist rebels in the northern 
province of eritrea have launched a major new offensive 
threatening government access to a vital port and food shipments to 
millions of drought victims 
the offensive which the rebels said began thursday along a 
120mile front ended a nearly yearlong lull in fighting in the 
region and plunged all four of ethiopias northern provinces back 
into civil war 
the government confirmed the new fighting friday night and a 
government radio station in asmara the capital of eritrea said 
battles were raging today 
in a statement the ethiopian government said the renewed 
fighting has now dimmed the prospects of resolving the eritrean 
problem through the stalled peace talks and accused the rebels of 
using the peace talks as a subterfuge to prepare extensively for 
this destructive war 
but a senior eritrean official said today in jiddah saudi 
arabia that the rebels will meet ethiopian government envoys in 
the north yemen capital of sana on feb 15 in a new bid to resolve 
their 28yearold conflict 
saleh ahmed ayai deputy chairman of the eritrean liberation 
frontunified organization told the associated press the talks 
were in response to a mediation effort by north yemens president 
ali abdullah saleh 
the meeting had earlier been tentatively set for feb 1 but it 
was postponed when saleh visited the united states 
former president jimmy carter sponsored similar peace talks 
between another eritrean faction the eritrean peoples liberation 
front and the addis ababa government late last year in atlanta and 
in nairobi kenya 
the eritreans secessionist campaign is africas longestrunning 
conflict 
the new offensive also has jeopardized plans by the united 
nations to provide food in the next few months for an estimated 4 
million drought victims in northern ethiopia mostly in the 
provinces of eritrea and tigre 
the attack by the eritrean peoples liberation front came as the 
government appeared to be containing another offensive farther 
south by the tigre peoples liberation front a separate insurgent 
group 
the government said the eritrean rebels main objective appeared 
to be the capture of massawa the largest of only two ports on 
ethiopias red sea coast the other is at asab near the countrys 
border with djibouti 
in a clandestine radio broadcast the rebels said they had taken 
control of the road from asmara to massawa 40 miles northeast of 
the provincial capital in what they described as a crushing 
offensive 
the operation was very broad and and swift and the victory 
very great said the voice of the broad masses of eritrea it 
claimed rebel forces had scattered the government army deployed 
along the road 
the eritrean rebels have been fighting for independence for 
their province once an italian colony since 1961 in what has 
become africas oldest war 
the tigrean rebels based in the province just south of eritrea 
launched their own offensive in august pushing government troops 
out of their last remaining strongholds in tigre and sweeping south 
and east into the provinces of wollo and gondor 
the government declared a mass mobilization in september in a 
counteroffensive in january it recaptured some of the towns and 
garrisons taken earlier by the tigrean insurgents 
although their aims are different the eritrean and tigrean 
rebels have coordinated attacks against the government in the past 
the tigreans unlike the eritreans seek the complete overthrow 
of the marxist regime of president mengistu haile marian and its 
replacement with what they describe as a government modeled after 
that of albania the last hardline communist government in eastern 
europe 
