<TEXT>
hundreds of workers and 
volunteers sopped up oily goo tarnishing miles of scenic beaches 
and boats skimmed crude from the water as the expanding slick from 
a ruptured tanker drifted northward 
the cleanup effort friday seemed no match for the spill of up to 
300000 gallons from the 811foot american trader methods to soak 
up the slippery viscous goo were inefficient some said 
this is a small oil spill said filmmaker jeanmichel 
cousteau son of renowned oceanographer jacques cousteau we 
dont know how to pick it up we do not have the technology we are 
not prepared 
the midweek spill from the british petroleumoperated tanker 
left oily globules along 18 miles of coastline from seal beach to 
newport beach where a dark brown tide marred the citys beaches 
officials there declared a state of emergency 
by morning southerly winds had blown the oil slick northward 
over two more miles of ocean lengthening it to 12 miles long 
medium concentrations of frothy windwhipped oil washed ashore 
along three miles of huntington beach said coast guard petty 
officer dennis hall 
winds turned offshore by sunrise sending fingers of the slick 
reaching westward expanding its width to 3 miles according to 
updated overflight charts 
hall said the slick reached northward to the long beach 
breakwater near anaheim bay he said long beach is a major ocean 
port adjacent to los angeles harbor another heavily traveled sea 
port a long breakwater protects both 
meanwhile los angeles harbor pilots struck today to protest 
what they called unsafe working conditions caused by fatigue and 
untrained pilots those pilots were not involved in the spill to 
the south in huntington beach 
two management pilot supervisors planned to steer four of nine 
scheduled tankers into port today but the ships would have to wait 
at offshore anchorages because dock workers honored the pilots 
strike the coast guard said 
several hundred workers hired by the oil shipper and an equal 
number of volunteers worked around the clock to soak up the goo at 
newport beach they filled hundreds of trash bags with towels 
fouled sand and oil 
are we out of the woods no not yet said charles webster 
crisis manager for british petroleum but were working to stay 
ahead of the curve 
workers in yellow waterproof gear combed the muck overnight near 
the huntington beach pier with a backhoe blotted oil with 
absorbent pads and dragged blue plastic pompons across the beach to 
soaked up oily pools 
residents scoured the sand with brooms and dust pans and carried 
oilsoaked sea birds to an emergency station but cleanup 
officials worried about chemical hazards and liability urged them 
to leave the job to hired crews 
british petroleum said 390 cleanup workers were cleaning a 
20mile coastal stretch from bolsa chica to laguna beach nine 
skimmers were at work on the slick a mile offshore and others were 
en route 
fiftyfour oilsoaked birds including 11 dead were reported 
friday by susan rimerman spokeswoman for international bird rescue 
and research a group hired by the state fish and game department 
department biologist john grant said 12 birds had died 
there were no reports of oil entering the wildlife habitats of 
the bolsa chica wetlands the santa ana river mouth and upper 
newport bay where booms blocked their entrances 
but there was concern the slick might drift south to laguna 
beach the scenic art colony fronted by rocky tide pools teeming 
with marine life webster said a cleanup company was placed on call 
there 
the coast guard pumped out 1 million gallons of oil still inside 
the forward hold of the tanker officials said the american trader 
which carried 21 million gallons of crude may have been gashed by 
its own anchor on wednesday as it tried to moor near a pipeline 
cousteau who flew over the slick early friday said the 
skimming equipment aboard the boats was not working 
you look at skimmers everybody is working very hard 
cousteau said it goes right under the boom i mean i filmed 
it there we are not being efficient and we do not have the 
technology to be efficient 
john turner director of the us fish and wildlife service 
said good weather had kept the slick offshore and available 
resources had helped cleanup efforts 
to date weve been lucky turner said but he warned that 
theres a lot of oil that could come ashore 
he said chemical dispersants would not be used due to the 
slicks proximity to shore and the potential danger of toxicity to 
animals fines and penalties were under consideration because of 
the dead and injured birds he said 
