<TEXT>
here are excerpts from some of 
the few public statements by nelson mandela since he was jailed in 
1962 
april 20 1964 at his trial before he was convicted of 
sabotage and sentenced to life in prison 
a time comes in the life of any nation where there remains 
only two choices submit or fight that time has now come to south 
africa we shall not submit and we have no choice but to hit back 
by all the means in our power in defense of our people our future 
our freedom 
during my lifetime i have dedicated myself to this struggle 
of the african people i have fought against white domination and i 
have fought against black domination 
i have cherished the ideal of a democratic and free society in 
which all persons live together in harmony and with equal 
opportunities 
it is an ideal which i hope to live for and achieve but if 
need be an ideal for which i am prepared to die 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
january 1985 to samuel dash american law professor and chief 
counsel for the senate watergate committee 
unlike white people anywhere else in africa whites in south 
africa belong here this is their home we want them to live here 
with us and to share power with us 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
feb 10 1985 rejecting president pw bothas offer of 
conditional release in statement read by his daughter zinzi 
let him botha renounce violence 
let him say that he will dismantle apartheid let him free 
all who have been imprisoned banished or exiled for their 
opposition to apartheid let him guarantee free political activity 
so that the people may decide who will govern them 
i cherish my own freedom dearly but i care even more for your 
freedom too many have died since i went to prison too many have 
suffered for the love of freedom i cannot sell my birthright 
nor am i prepared to sell the birthright of the people to be free 
only free men can negotiate i cannot and will not give 
any undertaking at a time when i and you the people are not free 
your freedom and mine cannot be separated i shall return 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
january 1989 to lord nicholas bethell a british member of 
the european parliament 
i am a socialist and i believe in a classless society 
the armed struggle was forced on us we go for hard 
targets only military installations and the symbols of apartheid 
civilians must not be touched 
all this can end as soon as talks begin it would be 
humiliating though for us simply to lay down our arms 
unconditionally 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
zulu leader mangosothu buthelezi a prominent black moderate 
and critic of the anc nothing the south african government can 
do will gain credibility while it treats dr mandela as a dangerous 
enemy black south africa will not rest until he is free 
i believe he would come out of jail to thump anybody who 
set black brother against black brother on the eve of a final 
victory over apartheid 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
dr nthato motlana an antiapartheid activist from soweto 
he is the one man who assuming he is willing could lead us out 
of this mess 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
helen suzman antiapartheid member of parliament who has 
visited mandela several times hes a man who has got 
surprisingly moderate views after all these years hes not 
embittered i believe he would genuinely attempt to negotiate 
some peaceful solution to south africas problems 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
samuel dash after meeting mandela in 1985 he appeared 
vigorous and healthy with a calm confident manner and dignified 
bearing that seemed incongruous in our prison surroundings i 
felt that i was in the presence not of a guerrilla fighter or 
radical ideologue but of a head of state 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the commonwealths eminent persons group which met mandela in 
1986 during an unsuccessful attempt to promote dialogue aimed at 
ending apartheid he is an isolated and lonely figure bearing 
his incarceration with courage and fortitude anxious to be 
reunited with his wife and family but determined that this can only 
be under circumstances which allow for his unconditional release 
his freedom is a key component in any hope of a peaceful 
resolution to a conflict which otherwise will prove allconsuming 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
president pw botha in january 1985 the government is 
