<DOCNO> AP900210-0069 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
watching american football on tv telephoning 
friends and writing a childrens book are among the simple 
pleasures author salman rushdie is permitted in his seclusion 
browsing through bookstores strolling down the street and going 
to movies are forbidden by the armed government guards who move him 
from one safe house to another to protect him from a yearold 
iranian death sentence 
rushdies whereabouts is unknown even to his wife american 
author marianne wiggins who moved out in august she says there 
are no marital problems and that she corresponds with husband each 
night 
after months of virtual silence rushdie and his wife have been 
telling a few trusted interviewers something about their year 
the things that are most difficult to take are not being able 
to walk down a street not being able to browse in a bookshop not 
being able to go to a movie those trivial sorts of things that 
you take for granted until you dont have them what they add up to 
is life rushdie told the independent on sunday in an interview 
behind drawn curtains at a restaurant 
his reading matter includes moby dick ulysses and the 
great freespeech defenders of the 18th century enlightenment 
rousseau diderot and voltaire 
he watches dallas dynasty and thirtysomething and 
confesses a new addiction to american football a recent addition 
to british tv 
rushdie told the newspaper that at times he could not work but 
now his writing is going well he is finishing a childrens 
book is putting together a collection of essays and has completed 
the synopsis for a novel 
</TEXT>
