<TEXT>
during his year in hiding author salman rushdie 
has published a poem several book reviews and a 7000word essay 
defending his novel the satanic verses here are some of the 
things he has said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
i recognize that moslems in many parts of the world are 
genuinely distressed by the publication of my novel i profoundly 
regret the distress that publication has occasioned to sincere 
followers of islam living as we do in a world of many faiths this 
experience has served to remind us that we must all be conscious of 
the sensibilities of others feb 18 1989 four days after the 
ayatollah ruhollah khomeini imposed the death sentence 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
i do not accept the charge of blasphemy because as somebody 
says in the satanic verses where there is no belief there 
is no blasphemy i am not a moslem it feels bizarre and wholly 
inappropriate to be described as some sort of heretic after having 
lived my life as a secular pluralist eclectic man feb 4 
1990 essay in the independent on sunday 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the things that are most difficult to take are not being able 
to walk down a street not being able to browse in a bookshop not 
being able to go to a movie those trivial sorts of things that 
you take for granted until you dont have them what they add up to 
is life feb 4 1990 interview in the independent on sunday 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
it has always been a shock to me to meet people for whom books 
simply do not matter and people who are scornful of the act of 
reading let alone writing it is perhaps always astonishing to 
learn that your beloved is not as attractive to others as she is to 
you feb 6 herbert read memorial lecture 
</TEXT>
