<TEXT>
eight bombs exploded in srinagar on 
saturday and moslem separatists urged city residents to 
demonstrate in the streets to mark the sixth anniversary of the 
execution of a militant leader 
police increased security and said srinagar would be under 
curfew throughout sunday the anniversary of mohammad maqbool 
butts death 
butt the founder of the militant jammukashmir liberation 
front was hanged in new delhis tihar jail on feb 11 1984 for 
the 1965 murder of an intelligence agent in kashmir 
butt was convicted in 1967 but he escaped from a srinagar jail 
in 1968 he was rearrested in 1979 and remained in jail until his 
execution 
the jammukashmir liberation front is spearheading a violent 
campaign for secession of the himalayan state of jammukashmir the 
countrys only moslem majority state from the predominantly hindu 
india 
the movement is centered in srinagar the summer capital of 
jammukashmir state and its largest city jammu region south of 
kashmir is hindu dominated 
at least 82 people have died in the latest round of secessionist 
violence that flared jan 20 when moslem militants took to the 
streets and clashed with security forces most victims were 
protesters shot for defying curfew 
curfew had been restricted to night hours since jan 26 because 
authorities said the situation had stabilized but it was clamped 
on the city at 11 am saturday after the bomb blasts 
police officials speaking on condition of anonymity said the 
blasts occurred outside two banks a post office and other shops 
and businesses they said no one was injured 
no one claimed responsibility but the officials blamed the 
separatists 
curfew was strictly enforced and streets remained deserted 
government officials speaking on condition of anonymity said the 
wall posters that exhorted people to mark butts execution were 
being removed 
some of the posters said come out and demonstrate in memory 
of martyr maqbool butt who laid down his life for the cause of 
liberation of kashmir 
witnesses who spoke on condition of anonymity said dozens of 
army trucks carrying soldiers rolled into srinagar late friday 
apparently to counter possible violence sunday 
the city of 1 million was virtually sealed 
troops with machine guns patrolled the outskirts all vehicles 
entering the city were stopped and searched all travelers were 
told to leave vehicles and stood in lines with their hands raised 
to be searched 
we are on full alert and we will stand no nonsense said 
major p govindaswamy in charge of the army checkpoint at 
panbazar five miles south of srinagar 
the army has been used often to control the violence in kashmir 
a strategic region bordering pakistan 
india accuses pakistan of arming and training the kashmiri 
militants pakistan denies the charge and says the kashmiris have 
the right to selfdetermination the countries have fought two wars 
over kashmir 
pakistans prime minister benazir bhutto appeared to issue a 
veiled threat saturday in a speech to parliament about the kashmir 
situation 
we want a peaceful solution but at the same time pakistan 
cannot be intimidated ms bhutto told pakistani lawmakers we 
know how to defend our freedom and independence she said 
ms bhutto accused india of blaming pakistan for the violence 
in an attempt to externalize and divert the issue 
kashmir was divided between india and pakistan after the two 
countries were partitioned following the end of british colonial 
rule in 1947 srinagar and the surrounding areas of the valley 
became part of jammukashmir 
