<TEXT>
the birth control pill ushered in the sexual 
revolution 30 years ago but there have been so few new 
contraceptives marketed in the united states since then that 
american women now find their choices limited 
we clearly have less available than other places said rep 
pat schroeder dcolo ticking off a list of contraceptives 
unavailable in the united states that includes longacting hormonal 
implants and injectables as well as the french abortion pill 
ru486 
planned parenthood federation of america is trying to build 
support for more contraceptive research with a series of 
conferences around the country including one scheduled monday in 
boston 
a joint committee of the national research council and the 
institute of medicine will release a report wednesday on the 
regulatory climate for development of new contraceptives 
more than 13 million american women use oral contraceptives 
known collectively as the pill 
used correctly the pill is 99 percent effective but its 
existence does not mean it can be used safely and effectively by 
everyone said rebecca stone director of public policy for the 
private center for population options 
the pill has some minor side effects must be taken daily and 
its not recommended for smokers over 35 and women with a history 
of bloodclotting disorders heart disease breast cancer 
estrogendependent tumors undiagnosed genital bleeding and a few 
other conditions 
in 1987 more than 8 million american women of reproductive age 
chose to be sterilized as a method of birth control while 69 
million relied on condoms 17 million used diaphragms 12 million 
chose spermicides 11 million had iuds and 11 million used 
contraceptive sponges 
also 23 million relied on withdrawal before ejaculation 17 
million used periodic abstinence and 33 million used nothing 
according to the alan guttmacher institute a private education and 
research group 
the food and drug administration soon is expected to approve a 
device called norplant which prevents pregnancy for up to five 
years 
the silicone rubber capsules each the size of a wooden 
matchstick are implanted in a womans upper arm but can be removed 
at any time to restore fertility it already is on the market in 12 
countries and is being tested in 40 others 
when the pill became available in the united states in 1960 
researchers predicted it was just the beginning that soon there 
would be more options including vaccines and a pill for men 
thirty years later the search for better contraceptives 
continues but the pace has slowed to a crawl 
in the early 1970s there were 13 major pharmaceutical companies 
eight in the united states conducting contraceptive research 
today there are three and only one is a us company ortho 
pharmaceutical corp 
a few smaller companies and nonprofit organizations are doing 
research 
the upjohn co fought a nearly 20year battle in an unsuccessful 
effort to win fda approval of depoprovera as a longacting 
injectable contraceptive it was opposed both by the religious 
right and feminist health groups that cited possible cancer risks 
depoprovera has been approved in more than 60 countries as a 
contraceptive including the united kingdom west germany norway 
sweden france and belgium it is approved in the united states to 
treat endometrial and renal cancers and because it is an approved 
drug some physicians do prescribe it as a contraceptive 
however doctors prescribing any drug for any other than its 
labeled use can face greater risk of liability 
some say the controversy over depoprovera helped chill the 
research climate but the fear of lawsuits is the most frequently 
cited reason for the dropoff in efforts to find new contraceptives 
other factors include insufficient federal funding high cost a 
cumbersome government approval process and spillover from the 
antiabortion movement 
stung by the fallout from ah robins cos intrauterine device 
the dalkon shield gd searle amp co went to court 19 times to 
defend its copper 7 iud plaintiffs alleged that the dalkon shield 
caused infections that led to infertility spontaneous abortions 
and in some cases death 
searle won 15 of the suits but discontinued its iud in 1986 
because it could no longer get liability insurance said 
spokeswoman kay bruno 
the ultimate loser is the american woman who doesnt have 
these options in contraception anymore bruno said 
only alza corps progestasert iud remained on the market after 
the dalkon shield controversy and only one new iud had been 
introduced since paragard made by gynopharma inc 
the government through the national institute of child health 
and human development and the agency for international development 
will spend about 20 million in 1990 on contraceptive research 
and development 
when other contraceptiverelated research is added such as 
evaluating existing birth control methods the total rises to about 
30 million 
dr gabriel bialy chief of the contraceptive development branch 
at the institute said research funds have been inadequate for 
years 
contraceptive development does not have too much political 
clout bialy said however he doesnt attribute the lack of 
interest to pressure from antiabortion groups some of which also 
oppose contraception 
we were not terribly popular even in the era of more liberal 
administrations 
others however say abortion politics is having an impact 
antiabortion forces persuaded congress in the 1970s to prohibit 
funding of research into contraceptive methods that work after 
pregnancy including the french abortion pill ru486 
ru486 approved in france and china can act after the 
implantation of a fertilized egg in france the pill cannot be 
used beyond the fifth week after fertilization or three weeks 
after a missed menstrual period 
a woman takes the drug orally and two days later is given an 
injection or suppository of synthetic prostaglandin which causes 
contractions of the uterus to ensure it has evacuated completely 
antiabortion groups have promised to boycott any company that 
attempts to bring ru486 to the united states 
prochoice activists are trying to channel emotional energy away 
from the abortion controversy into contraceptive research 
it seems to me if we want to reduce the number of abortions 
we need to reduce the number of unintended pregnancies with 
better contraceptive options said rep olympia snowe rmaine 
schroeder and snowe are sponsoring a bill to establish three 
birth control research centers and two infertility research 
centers emphasizing research on new drugs and devices 
abortion foes oppose the bill which calls for 772 million to 
be spent over five years because it was written to permit 
federally funded research on abortion methods said douglas 
johnson a spokesman for the national right to life committee 
despite the controversy dr j joseph speidel president of the 
nonprofit population crisis committee is optimistic 
i dont think you can stop scientific progress he said i 
think well have some new contraceptives available but a lot 
of other countries will have them first 
 
