of funds from other voa accounts 
usia directed us to solve the problem and find a way to keep 
broadcasting robert coonrod voas deputy director said 
saturday congressional approval of the funding still was 
uncertain he added 
chittavoravong loved listening to the voa back in vientiane the 
capital of the isolated southeast asian nation 
chittavoravong taught english at the laoamerican culture center 
and also at a teachers college he also taught laotian to diplomats 
at the australian british and us embassies 
soon after the communist pathet lao movement seized power in 
1975 a truck pulled up to the teachers college soldiers sought 
out chittavoravong handcuffed him and took him away 
the slightly built teacher was accused of being a spy for the 
cia no charges were ever brought against him and there was no 
trial 
for two and ahalf years chittavoravong shared a jail hall with 
about 250 inmates sleeping on a wooden floor with a blanket and 
mosquito net as cover 
chittavoravong was among a favored few whose families were 
allowed to bring them food once a month 
every night inmates sat crosslegged on the floor in groups of 
10 and conducted selfcriticism sessions in which they 
confessed their thoughts and misdeeds of the day typical 
confessions would consist of an inmate telling how he stole a 
banana from someones food package from home 
once every few weeks chittavoravong was required to write about 
his past sometimes at great length and sometimes in abbreviated 
form they were trying to confuse us and to find 
discrepancies he said in an interview 
occasionally chittavoravong heard gunshots but information 
about the shootings was hard to obtain i tried to be a good boy 
i didnt want to be punished he said 
in a suburb of vientiane his mother prayed to her ancestors 
spirits for her sons release she sacrificed pigs heads and 
pledged that if released her son would become a monk 
chittavoravongs incarceration ended as abruptly as it began 
one spring day in 1979 he was told he had been reeducated and 
was free to go but chittavoravong had by then decided to go much 
farther than his suburban home this system was not human he 
said i decided it was either death or freedom 
first however he had to fulfill his mothers vow so he shaved 
his head and entered a monastery 
at night lying under a blanket on his narrow cot 
chittavoravong listened to the outlawed broadcasts of the voice of 
america then as now it was the only western radio that could be 
heard in the landlocked country 
he planned his escape with the help of a relative who drove him 
to the banks of the mekong he was hidden by another relative until 
it was deemed safe for him to attempt the swim to thailand he took 
with him several personal documents some thai money a pair of 
pants and a shirt all of which he kept dry in an inner tube 
but his ordeal was not over yet upon reaching thailand 
chittavoravong was thrown into a small jail he had enough money to 
eventually bribe his way out and reach a un refugee camp from 
there he obtained a visa to come here 
now with four children and a new mortgage the 50yearold 
broadcaster feels his world is coming apart again i dont know 
what i can do its so sad i love this job he said 
voa has promised to help the laidoff employees find new jobs 
but lao service chief linthong noinala is doubtful that more than 
one or two can find jobs comparable to their current positions 
linthong a 22year voa veteran whose wife died last month is 
disconsolate we will survive we will do what we have to even if 
its cooking or cleaning but i dont understand why they are doing 
this to us 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

