here is a text of the question 
and answer session of president fw de klerks news conference on 
saturday announcing that black nationalist leader nelson mandela 
would be freed the text was provided to the associated press by 
the presidents office 
question do you believe this now fulfills all the preconditions 
for the usa and other countries to lift sanctions against south 
africa 
de klerk we are not working against checklists we are doing 
what we sincerely believe to be in the best interests of south 
africa obviously there are still some of the preconditions which 
have been set by various sources which have not literally been met 
but the most important stumbling blocks in the way of negotiation 
in the way of positive developments to create a climate for 
negotiation have now been addressed to my mind 
question mr president will the state lend security personnel 
and apparatus to ensure mr mandelas safety and secondly do you 
expect that he will depart tomorrow for his home in soweto 
de klerk the question of security and the actual process of 
release is that which is being discussed now with interested 
parties by officials of the government the state will secure the 
position of mr mandela while he is in custody of the state as 
regards the rest of your question when mr mandela is released he 
becomes a free man and he does not owe it to me to inform us of his 
program i have not asked him about it either 
question mr president you said that mr mandela has committed 
himself to a peaceful solution in south africa does that mean that 
he now officially rejects violence 
de klerk i do not intend to speak on behalf of mr mandela this 
afternoon he will be able to do so tomorrow 
question a number of people who have met with mr mandela since 
your original meeting have spoken about it very positively and 
about the chemistry that exists between you and him i wonder if 
you can tell us about your impressions of him and give us some kind 
of idea of the exchanges that you have had 
de klerk the discussions really took place in a very civil 
atmosphere he is a friendly man i would like to think that i am 
also a friendly man yes the discussions really took place in good 
spirit he is an elderly dignified man and he is an interesting 
man 
question mr president the minister of constitutional 
development said that the state of emergency could be lifted within 
weeks is that a fair assessment on your part now after meeting 
with mr mandela 
de klerk as it is clearly stated in my statement the final 
test is the situation on the ground and everything will depend 
upon the question whether we get an increase in unrest or whether 
we get a decrease in unrest 
question mr president mr mandela has made clear over the 
past few weeks that he was uncomfortable being released in a 
situation where the state of emergency was still in force and not 
all political prisoners had been freed what was his reaction to 
you informing him of his release into those conditions 
de klerk once again i really do not want to speak on his 
behalf i can only give impressions and i went to great lengths to 
explain why the situation is as it is with regard to the state of 
emergency and that partiular question you must ask him tomorrow 
question mr de klerk how are you going to release mr 
mandela are you going to release him from the prison straight into 
freedom or are you going to take him away 
de klerk that is part of the process that is being discussed by 
officials now i wont be present and i do not intend to interfere 
in the detail 
question you spoke of an increase or decrease in violence what 
judgement or basis are you going to use for determining whether you 
feel there has indeed been the right climate established for doing 
away with the regulations 
de klerk well obviously any government has sources of 
information available to it it is official sources reports from 
its security forces its police wherever they are factual reports 
which come in regularly which are all assimilated at one central 
point analyzed and studied we deal with such things in a very 
scientific manner and we know what is going on in every corner of 
the country 
question what i meant sir you know that you are going to be 
subjected to some considerable scrutiny is there some sort of norm 
that you have established that you can set out for us now as to 
what would constitute stability 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

