<TEXT>
the superpowers on saturday announced preliminary 
agreement on a us plan for a 10year phaseout of their chemical 
weapons stockpiles that links their total elimination to a 
negotiated worldwide ban 
soviet foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze told a news 
conference after three days of talks with us secretary of state 
james a baker iii that the superpowers reached accord on the draft 
of a prospective agreement of principle 
we believe such an agreement could be signed during president 
gorbachevs visit to the united states he added 
soviet leader mikhail s gorbachev is to travel to washington in 
june to meet with president bush 
the announcement had been expected after the lengthy talks baker 
had with shevardnadze and gorbachev in moscow 
in a joint statement carried by the official soviet news agency 
tass the united states and soviet union pledged to work out an 
agreement for destruction of a significant part of their 
chemical arsenals the agreed reductions would put their stocks at 
equally low levels while 40nation talks on a worldwide ban 
continue in geneva 
when an international ban on the development production use 
and possession of chemical weapons enters into force the united 
states and soviet union will further cut stocks to a very small 
fraction of current arsenals over an eightyear period the 
statement said 
in the following two years remaining us and soviet chemical 
weapons would be destroyed it said 
the statement said all states capable of manufacturing chemical 
weapons must adhere to the convention indicating that if any third 
country refused to join a ban the superpowers would not be 
obligated to liquidate their remaining stockpiles 
only the united states and soviet union admit to having chemical 
weapons although a dozen nations including libya and iraq are 
thought to have production capability 
the geneva conference negotiating a global chemical weapons ban 
opened its 1990 session wednesday the conference dates to 1968 
diplomats for years have forecast an agreement soon although 
progress in separate bilateral ussoviet talks that began five 
years ago have now spurred optimism that a treaty might be signed 
within a year 
in december the superpowers exchanged confidential data on the 
size of their arsenals the chief soviet negotiator at the geneva 
negotiations sergei batsanov said last month there was no 
surprise implying his country believes it backed up its public 
claim that it has no more than 50000 tons of chemical arms 
some us analysts however have said the soviet arsenal is 
more than six times larger than that batsanovs former us 
counterpart at the geneva talks max friedersdorf said in december 
the soviets have considerably more than 50000 tons us 
stockpiles are estimated at 30000 tons 
in september bush offered to destroy 80 percent of the us 
chemical arsenal before an international treaty is reached if 
moscow follows suit the soviets however said then such 
reductions should be accompanied by a halt to production of new 
chemical weapons 
that demand would put an end to the us program to replace part 
of its obsolete stockpile with modern binary chemical weapons 
composed of two relatively harmless agents that become dangerous 
when mixed 
the ussoviet statement issued saturday said only that the 
international treaty should provide for a halt to production of new 
chemical weapons meaning us manufacture of binaries could 
continue until such a pact enters into force 
