<TEXT>
an emerging chemical weapons accord and 
significant progress on arms control marked a mostly successful 
marathon negotiating mission here by secretary of state james a 
baker iii that wound up saturday with an unprecedented live debate 
with soviet legislators 
the net result before baker flew off to sofia for talks with 
government and opposition forces in bulgaria an east european 
country in a rocky transition from hard line communism is that 
president bush and soviet president mikhail s gorbachev can 
anticipate signing possibly two accords to curb chemical and 
nuclear weapons when they meet at the summit in washington in june 
in an exceptionally glowing joint statement issued before 
bakers departure the superpowers stressed that while certain 
significant differences remain between them the relationship 
is increasingly marked by understanding cooperation and the 
search for mutual advantage 
the evidence was striking during the four days of talks baker 
held with foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze and a long 
session friday with gorbachev who was still savoring his historic 
victory within the communist party 
at gorbachevs behest the central committee agreed to revoke 
the partys monopoly on political power and set the stage for 
political competition that might have gorbachev running for 
reelection as president 
surprisingly gorbachev told reporters lets wait and see 
when they asked whether he would make such a race as a communist 
the most significant result of the negotiations was an 
unexpected breakthrough on sealaunched cruise missiles the most 
difficult in a handful of knotty problems standing in the way of a 
treaty to reduce us and soviet longrange nuclear missiles 
bombers and submarines by 30 percent to 50 percent 
baker and the soviets agreed to take the cruise missiles out of 
the strategic weapons treaty that the two sides hope to sign at the 
june summit meeting instead the cruise missiles will be dealt 
with in a separate side statement that evidently will not be 
submitted along with the treaty to the senate for ratification 
for the first time baker openly acknowledged there is no sure 
way to verify how many of the weapons carried by submarines and 
surface fighting ships the other side has on board 
he did not disclose what the statements would contain but 
separating the issue from the treaty is likely to improve the 
prospects for a june signing ceremony at the white house 
after years of handwringing and stopstart negotiating efforts 
meanwhile baker and the soviets worked out a formula for 
destroying us and soviet chemical weapons stocks 
the emerging agreement also slated for a summit signing 
provides for substantial reductions over eight years in stocks of 
us and soviet poison gas to be followed by the elimination of 
all chemical weapons provided that dozens of other nations 
negotiating in geneva agree to abolish their stockpiles as well 
the outcome was a diplomatic triumph for the bush administration 
when the president advanced his proposal last year the soviets 
questioned the us determination to retain 2 percent of the deadly 
weapons until all nations capable of producing them signed the 
international accord 
the joint statement indicated the soviets had accepted bushs 
formula 
there also was marked progress toward a third arms control 
agreement gorbachev countered bushs state of the union proposal 
for a ceiling of 195000 us and soviet troops in central europe 
with a suggestion that the ceiling be extended to superpower forces 
on foreign soil throughout europe 
this would mean withdrawing the 30000 american soldiers that 
bushs initiative would leave in britain greece italy spain and 
turkey 
alternatively gorbachev said he would go along with bushs 
overall european ceiling of 225000 troops this would give the 
soviets leeway to have 225000 soldiers in central europe where 
most of the red army is based 
baker called gorbachevs approach very close to the 
presidents proposal but delayed a response until he meets with 
the foreign ministers of the 15 north atlantic treaty organization 
allies in ottawa canada on monday and tuesday 
even on a technical level the us arms control agenda moved 
ahead 
agreement was reached for a full disclosure of data from 
strategic missile tests and to set a ceiling on us and soviet 
landbased mobile missiles that will be kept in storage under the 
emerging strategic weapons limitation treaty 
also the two sides decided on limiting the cruise missiles 
carried by their bombers but could not agree on how to restrict 
the range of the missiles carried on the bombers 
on the other hand baker clashed with the soviets over the 
ongoing delivery of latemodel mig29 fighter bombers to cuba he 
acknowledged he could not persuade gorbachev and shevardnadze to 
keep the weapons out of president fidel castros hands 
baker concluded his visit with a 90minute appearance before the 
international affairs committee of the supreme soviet he is the 
first us official to appear before the legislative body an event 
he attributed to gorbachevs policy of openness 
 
baker then flew to sofia for separate meetings with government 
and opposition leaders he has criticized the country for the slow 
pace of its reform but prime minister andrei lukanov told 
reporters we are prepared to accept without any hesitation the 
wishes of the people 
lukanov appealed an expansion of us trade which now consists 
primarily of bulgaria shipping wine and tobacco to the united 
states in exchange for grain 
lukanov said the government was open for a dialogue with all 
political forces i mean it 
baker met first with the government leaders and urged them to 
conduct a free and fair election a senior us official said 
he also stressed the importance of not forcing the assimilation 
of ethnic turks who past regimes were charged compelling to adopt 
bulgarian names and to abandon their cultural and moslem religious 
practices 
the official who briefed reporters on condition of anonymity 
said baker stressed that the credibility of the government 
depends on how the elections are carried out 
then meeting with 17 members of the union of democratic forces 
an opposition coalition baker heard stories of political 
imprisonment in prior years and difficulty in preparing for the 
election because of newsprint shortages and problems in getting 
organizing throughout the country 
you can win if you stay united baker said he told 
reporters later the administration was reserving judgment in 
the contest 
on sunday baker flies to bucharest for a slightly longer than 
fourhour visit to the romanian capital 
in his appearance before the soviet legislators baker spoke 
from a podium with a marble bust of lenin peering over his shoulder 
and borrowed the title of the arthur koestler novel in recalling 
the darkness at noon that preceded gorbachevs rise to power in 
1985 
today we see reason return baker said today i come 
before the founding fathers of a new soviet union a new soviet 
union you are building 
but he then lectured the soviets against spending badly needed 
resources supporting marxist governments in cuba nicaragua angola 
and cambodia 
baker contrasted that activity with gorbachevs policy of 
noninterference in europe where the soviet leaders actions 
have played a vital role in supporting the creation of legitimate 
governments 
on the other hand baker said we remain especially disturbed 
by the military shipments your government continues to send to 
those seeking military solutions to conflicts in regions vital to 
us 
he added this is even less comprehensible when it happens at 
a time when your people clearly need those scarce resources put to 
good use at home 
several of the legislators responded in a questionandanswer 
session with attacks on the bush administrations refusal to engage 
in naval disarmament talks and to halt nuclear weapons tests they 
also criticized the invasion of panama 
gen sergei akhromeyev gorbachevs military adviser questioned 
the modest reductions in us military spending in contrast to what 
he said was a 14 percent slash in soviet spending and he said the 
united states had not dismantled dozens of military bases that have 
surrounded the soviet union for 45 years 
baker defended the panama invasion as a unique us use of force 
to remove gen manuel antonio noriega whom baker called a thug 
