<TEXT>
james f gordon a former federal judge 
who drafted a busing plan to desegregate louisville schools 15 
years ago died friday at age 71 of complications following lung 
surgery 
a resident of venice fla for the last three years gordon 
died at sarasota memorial hospital 
gordon became a senior judge with a reduced caseload in july 
1976 and retired in january 1984 after 18 years on the bench 
in 1973 as a us district judge gordon dismissed a lawsuit 
against jefferson county public schools by a coalition of 
civilrights groups but after an appeals court reversed his ruling 
and ordered that busing begin in september 1975 gordon drafted a 
plan he later called the best in the country 
he eventually said he had concluded that busing had helped 
blacks and whites know one another better 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
david stivender chorus master of the 
metropolitan opera since 1973 died friday in pittsburgh of 
congestive heart failure at age 56 
he had been a member of the mets conducting staff since 1978 
his responsibilities included preparing the chorus for a season 
that usually includes two dozen operas he also selected singers 
from the approximately 300 who auditioned each year 
born in milwaukee he began studying the piano and became 
interested in opera at age 12 
he studied composition at northwestern university and joined 
the opera arts workshop in atlanta in 1957 he became an assistant 
conductor at the lyric opera of chicago in 1960 and conducted at 
the festival of two worlds in spoleto italy in 1963 and 1964 
he wrote mascagni a 1988 book based on the composers 
dictated memoirs and other writings presented in autobiographical 
form 
</TEXT>
